{
  "doc_id": "20348",
  "text": "The oligomerization state of enolase has always been an interesting issue. Most enolases are dimers in solution [CITATION_1] but enolase octamers have not been rare either [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . A previous study proposed that the length of the loop connecting H4 helix and S4 strand is possibly a key factor determining enolase octamerization [CITATION_5] . A long H4/S4 loop corresponds to enolase dimer, while a short loop could lead to the octamer formation. The assay data of this work supports this viewpoint as SS2 enolase contains a short loop in this position and indeed forms the octamer both in crystal and in solution.",
